HEADWORD: Counterscarp
<hw>Coun"ter*scarp`</hw> <pr>(koun`t⟦etil⟧r*sk⟦aum⟧rp`)</pr>
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Counter-</ets> + <ets>scarp</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>contrescarpe</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>The exterior
slope or wall of the ditch; -- sometimes, the whole covered way, beyond
the ditch, with its parapet and glacis; <as>as, the enemy have lodged
themselves on the <ex>counterscarp</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Counterseal</ent>⟦br⟧
